Each distinct chord length occurs 7 times, corresponding to \( k = 1, 2, 3 \). The sum of the 4th powers of these lengths is given by: \[ 7 \left( [2 \sin(\pi/7)]^4 + [2 \sin(2\pi/7)]^4 + [2 \sin(3\pi/7)]^4 \right) \] Using the trigonometric identity \( \sin^4(x) = \frac{3 - 4 \cos(2x) + \cos(4x)}{8} \), we convert each term: \[ [2 \sin(k\pi/7)]^4 = 16 \sin^4(k\pi/7) = 16 \left( \frac{3 - 4 \cos(2k\pi/7) + \cos(4k\pi/7)}{8} \right) = 2 \left( 3 - 4 \cos(2k\pi/7) + \cos(4k\pi/7) \right) \] Summing these for \( k = 1, 2, 3 \): \[ 16 \left( \frac{3 - 4 \cos(2\pi/7) + \cos(4\pi/7) + 3 - 4 \cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(8\pi/7) + 3 - 4 \cos(6\pi/7) + \cos(12\pi/7)}{8} \right) \] Simplifying using symmetry and roots of unity, we find: \[ \cos(2\pi/7) + \cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(6\pi/7) = -\frac{1}{2} \] Thus, the sum of the 4th powers becomes: \[ 112 \left( \frac{9}{8} - \frac{3}{8} \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right) \right) = 112 \left( \frac{21}{16} \right) = 147 \] Finally, taking the result modulo 100: \[ 147 \mod 100 = 47 \] The remainder when the answer is divided by 100 is \(\boxed{47}\).
